If you're out of it for a long time /but still consuming art/, you may suffer or "notice" something akin to regression upon picking it back up. However, if you return to drawing with some measure of consistency, you should see yourself where you left off - and progressing from there! - once you're as vigorously pursuing it and having fun with it as you were before you left off. In s o m e cases, I find creative refractory periods, or vacations as it were, are important during periods of extreme duress, personal turmoil, trauma, and the like, to avoid wrapping-up creative passions in emotional burnout.
I say "some" because creative pursuits also offer great mediums for escape and catharsis during those times. I've just found that, as an adult, it's been harder for me to return to & pursue my own passions because they occasionally "take me back," if that makes sense. Especially when I meander over worrying about progress. I only enjoyed sketching and doodling last year /because/ I'd totally relinquished any personal obligations in it and had fun doodleposting. Work took such precedent over anything else at the time (admittedly unhealthy), I caved when I worried more about improving.
